11. Container With Most Water
You are given an integer array height of length n. There are n vertical lines drawn such that the two endpoints of the ith line are (i, 0) and (i, height[i]).

Find two lines that together with the x-axis form a container, such that the container contains the most water.

Return the maximum amount of water a container can store.

Notice that you may not slant the container.

Example 1:

Input: height = [1,8,6,2,5,4,8,3,7]
Output: 49
Explanation: The above vertical lines are represented by array [1,8,6,2,5,4,8,3,7]. In this case, the max area of water (blue section) the container can contain is 49.
Example 2:

Input: height = [1,1]
Output: 1

Brute-Force Approach:Using nested loop and finding the maxarea with each subarray elements

Time Complexity: O(n2)
Space Complexity: O(1)

Solution:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
     int arr[]={1,8,6,2,5,4,8,3,7};
     System.out.println(MaximumWater(arr));
    }
   public static int MaximumWater(int arr[]){
     int maxArea=0;
    for(int left=0;left<arr.length;left++){
      for(int right=left+1;right<arr.length;right++){
        int width=right-left;
        int height= Math.min(arr[left],arr[right]);
        int area=width*height;
        maxArea=Math.max(area,maxArea);
      }
    }
    return maxArea;
   }
}

Optimal Approach : Using Two- pointers

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)

Solution:-
public class Solution {
    public int maxArea(int[] height) {
        int maxwater=0;
        int left=0;
        int right=height.length-1;

        while(left<right){
            int width=right-left;
            int currWater=Math.min(height[left],height[right]) * width;
            maxwater= Math.max(currWater, maxwater);
            if(height[left]<height[right]){
                left++;
            }else{
                right--;
            }
        }
        return maxwater;
    }
}


